## TypeScript Types

Define types in `src/lib/salesforce-queries.ts`. Always type the jsforce query
result — `conn.query<T>()` accepts a generic.

```ts
export type SfLineItem = {
  Id: string;
  Name: string;
  Line_Item_Number__c: string | null;
  Product_Name__c: string | null;
  SAP_Product_Code__c: string | null;
  Quantity__c: number | null;
  Sales_Price__c: number | null;
  Total_Price__c: number | null;
  WBS__c: string | null;
  Description__c: string | null;
  Start_Date__c: string | null;  // ISO date string
  End_Date__c: string | null;
};

export type SfCallForResources = {
  Id: string;
  Name: string;
  Account__c: string | null;
  Account__r: { Name: string } | null;
  Contract__c: string | null;
  Contract__r: { ContractNumber: string; Name: string } | null;
  Document_Status__c: string | null;
  Signed_Date__c: string | null;
  Counterpart_Reference__c: string | null;
  Total_Price__c: number | null;
  Call_For_Resources_Line_Items__r: {
    totalSize: number;
    records: SfLineItem[];
  } | null;
};
```

**All custom fields are nullable** — Salesforce returns `null` for empty fields, never
`undefined`. Always guard with `?? null` or `?? 0` before using values in calculations.

