## Error Handling

jsforce throws on auth failure, network errors, and SOQL syntax errors. All errors
surface as generic 500 — never expose Salesforce error details to the client.

Common errors and their causes:

| Error message | Cause | Fix |
|---|---|---|
| `INVALID_LOGIN` | Wrong username/password/token combo | Check `SF_SECURITY_TOKEN` — it changes when you reset your password |
| `INVALID_FIELD` | API name wrong in SOQL | Run `sf-describe.ts` to get the correct name |
| `INVALID_TYPE` | Object API name wrong | Verify object name ends in `__c` |
| `MALFORMED_QUERY` | SOQL syntax error | Check subquery parentheses and relationship name ends in `__r` |
| Connection timeout | Sandbox may be sleeping | Sandbox orgs sleep after inactivity — first request wakes them, retry once |

For sandbox environments, add a retry on the first connection attempt since sleeping
sandboxes timeout on the first login request.

---

## Rules for Cursor

1. **Never write SOQL inline in route files** — all queries go in `src/lib/salesforce-queries.ts`.
2. **Always use the singleton** from `src/lib/salesforce.ts` — never create a new connection.
3. **Always type query results** — use `conn.query<SfCallForResources>(soql)`, never `any`.
4. **All custom Salesforce fields are nullable** — always handle `null` before using values.
5. **Run `sf-describe.ts` first** when adding new fields — never guess API names.
6. **Child records come from a subquery**, not a second query — use `FROM ChildRelationship__r`
   inside parentheses in the parent SELECT.
7. **Never write back to Salesforce** from this app — this integration is read-only.
8. **Never log Salesforce credentials or raw error objects** to the console in production.
9. **Use sandbox for dev** — set `SF_LOGIN_URL=https://test.salesforce.com` in `.env.local`.
10. **Follow the same API route conventions** as all other routes — Zod, try/catch,
    guard clauses, `{ error: string }` on failure, no raw Salesforce errors to the client.
